Last week we focused on the first data set, so the x and y variables that end in "1". Letâs continue to focus on the first data set today.

a1 <- anscombe %>% 
  select(ends_with("1")) %>% 
  rename(x = x1, y = y1)

a1 %>% glimpse()
## Rows: 11
## Columns: 2
## $ x <dbl> 10, 8, 13, 9, 11, 14, 6, 4, 12, 7, 5
## $ y <dbl> 8.04, 6.95, 7.58, 8.81, 8.33, 9.96, 7.24, 4.26, 10.84, 4.82, 5.68

Visualizing the relationship between x and y as a scatter plot.

a1 %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point(size = 5.5) +
  theme_bw()

Want to display text at specific points in the plot. Itâs useful supplemental information. A simple type of supplemental information to display is the row order index on a point. Our data set does not include such an index.

a1
##     x     y
## 1  10  8.04
## 2   8  6.95
## 3  13  7.58
## 4   9  8.81
## 5  11  8.33
## 6  14  9.96
## 7   6  7.24
## 8   4  4.26
## 9  12 10.84
## 10  7  4.82
## 11  5  5.68

We could manually add in a column for the row index, but the tibble package which is part of tidyverse has the rowid_to_column() to help out.

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column()
##    rowid  x     y
## 1      1 10  8.04
## 2      2  8  6.95
## 3      3 13  7.58
## 4      4  9  8.81
## 5      5 11  8.33
## 6      6 14  9.96
## 7      7  6  7.24
## 8      8  4  4.26
## 9      9 12 10.84
## 10    10  7  4.82
## 11    11  5  5.68

Include the rowid as text on the plot. The text is a geometric object. It has aesthetics, such as the x and y coordinate positions. And the label which is what we want to display at the position. There are two ways of showing text objects, the geom_label() and geom_text().

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_label(mapping = aes(label = rowid)) +
  theme_bw()

If we change the theme to a dark them the label âbubbleâ by default is still white color.

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_label(mapping = aes(label = rowid)) +
  theme_dark()

geom_text() is more streamlined, it only shows the text label and does not include the âbubbleâ around the text.

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = rowid)) +
  theme_bw()

We can modify the size of the text with the size aesthetic.

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = rowid),
            size = 8.5) +
  theme_bw()

We can also change the color.

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = rowid),
            size = 8.5, color = 'red') +
  theme_bw()

We can combine multiple geometric objects together to creat a multi layered graphic. We add layers together to âbuild upâ the final graphic.

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = rowid)) +
  theme_bw()

Letâs modify the points so that we have larger points of a darker color with text of a lighter color on top.

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point(size = 7.5, color = 'black') +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = rowid),
            color = 'white') +
  theme_bw()

Text aesthetics can be mapped to variables in the data set. So letâs try the text color and size mapped to the rowid.

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point(size = 10, color = 'grey') +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = rowid,
                          color = rowid,
                          size = rowid)) +
  scale_color_viridis_c() +
  scale_size_continuous() +
  theme_bw()

So letâs use a fill aesthetic for the markers and a color aesthetic for the font color. Specify a marker shape that has both fill and color stroke.

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point(size = 10,
             mapping = aes(fill = rowid),
             shape = 21, color = 'black', stroke = 1.) +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = rowid,
                          color = rowid > 6)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c() +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("TRUE" = 'black',
                                "FALSE" = 'white')) +
  theme_bw()

Turn off the legend guide for the text color and the marker fill.

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point(size = 10,
             mapping = aes(fill = rowid),
             shape = 21, color = 'black', stroke = 1.) +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = rowid,
                          color = rowid > 6)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(guide = FALSE) +
  scale_color_manual(guide = FALSE,
                     values = c("TRUE" = 'black',
                                "FALSE" = 'white')) +
  theme_bw()

Lines and paths

When we want to express continuity we want to use lines. The geom_line() lets us express continuity in the x-axis variable. So geom_line() connects sequential points based on the value of the x aesthetic. For small data sets, I like to combine geom_line() and geom_point() so I can see the exact data points getting connected. To see why letâs first just look at the geom_line().

a1 %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_line() +
  theme_bw()

Combining the line with the points lets us see that the âkinksâ or the âmountain topsâ are associated with data points.

a1 %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  theme_bw()

The line is choppy because thereâs scatter in the data. Lines have aesthetics size is the line thickness, linetype controls if the line is solid, dashed, dotted, etcâ¦

Letâs now combine the point, the text, and the line in our graphic.

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_line(size = 1.) +
  geom_point(size = 10,
             mapping = aes(fill = rowid),
             shape = 21, color = 'black', stroke = 1.) +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = rowid,
                          color = rowid > 6)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(guide = FALSE) +
  scale_color_manual(guide = FALSE,
                     values = c("TRUE" = 'black',
                                "FALSE" = 'white')) +
  theme_bw()

There is another way to express continuityâ¦we can consider the row order in the data set. The geom_path() object connects points as the appear in the data.

a1 %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_path() +
  theme_bw()

Why is it all over the place? Because the âpathâ follows the sequential ROW ORDER not the sequential x-axis ordering.

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_path(size = 1.55) +
  geom_point(size = 10,
             mapping = aes(fill = rowid),
             shape = 21, color = 'black', stroke = 1.) +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = rowid,
                          color = rowid > 6)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(guide = FALSE) +
  scale_color_manual(guide = FALSE,
                     values = c("TRUE" = 'black',
                                "FALSE" = 'white')) +
  theme_bw()

Combine the geom_line() and the geom_path() a thick transparent for the path and a red dashed line for the sequential x-axis line.

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_path(size = 4.5, color = 'black', alpha = 0.25) +
  geom_line(size = 1.25, color = 'red', linetype = 'dashed') +
  geom_point(size = 10,
             mapping = aes(fill = rowid),
             shape = 21, color = 'black', stroke = 1.) +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = rowid,
                          color = rowid > 6)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(guide = FALSE) +
  scale_color_manual(guide = FALSE,
                     values = c("TRUE" = 'black',
                                "FALSE" = 'white')) +
  theme_bw()

The âbest fit lineâ or regression line requires a statistical transformation and is considered its own geometric object. In ggplot2 itâs known as the geom_smooth(). One way to âsmoothâ is with a linear trend. By default the geom_smooth() allows for a non-linear smoother, and so to force a linear relationship which want to specify method = lm and the formula = y ~ x.

a1 %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point(size = 5.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = lm) +
  theme_bw()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Specify the formula to remove the message.

a1 %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point(size = 5.5) +
  geom_smooth(formula = y ~ x,
              method = lm) +
  theme_bw()

To turn off the confidence interval set se = FALSE.

a1 %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point(size = 5.5) +
  geom_smooth(formula = y ~ x,
              method = lm,
              se = FALSE) +
  theme_bw()

Combine the points, text, line, path, and trend.

a1 %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_path(size = 4.5, color = 'black', alpha = 0.25) +
  geom_line(size = 1.25, color = 'red', linetype = 'dashed') +
  geom_point(size = 10,
             mapping = aes(fill = rowid),
             shape = 21, color = 'black', stroke = 1.) +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = rowid,
                          color = rowid > 6)) +
  geom_smooth(formula = y ~ x,
              method = lm,
              se = FALSE,
              size = 1.55) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(guide = FALSE) +
  scale_color_manual(guide = FALSE,
                     values = c("TRUE" = 'black',
                                "FALSE" = 'white')) +
  theme_bw()
